     "She came up the path with two little dogs at her heels."

   pat sb/yourself on the back - (informal) to praise somebody or yourself for doing something well
   a pat on the back (for sth/for doing sth) - ​(informal) praise or approval for something that you have done well
     "He deserves a pat on the back for all his hard work."
     "Give yourself a pat on the back!" - возьми с полки пирожок
   pat sb down - обыскивать (to search someone for weapons, drugs, etc. by touching their clothes):
     "The police handcuffed him and patted him down."

   pluck sth out of the air - взять с потолка (to say a name, number, etc. without thinking about it, especially in answer to a question):
     "I just plucked a figure out of the air and said : ‘Would £1 000 seem reasonable to you?’"
   out of thin air - из воздуха, из ниоткуда (from nowhere or nothing, as if by magic):
     "Unfortunately, I can’t just conjure up the money out of thin air!"
     "I can't come up with €10,000 out of thin air."
     "They built the cell phone industry out of thin air in the mid-1980s."

   on a level/par with sb/sth (see also: alongside?) - наряду, наравне, на одном уровне (​as good, bad, important, etc. as sb/sth else):
     "This place is on a level with the best French restaurants."
     "The regeneration of the city's downtown dock front will put it on a par with Nice or Cannes."

   jog sb's memory - освежить воспоминания (to cause you to remember something):
     "Seeing her again jogged my memory, and I recalled my life as a child on a farm in Minnesota."
     "Maybe these letters will help to jog your memory."

   sink or swim - to be in a situation where you will either succeed by your own efforts or fail completely:
     "The new students were just left to sink or swim."
     "In a situation like this, you either sink or swim."
     "My employer gave me no help when I started my new job - I was just left to sink or swim."
   sink to such a level/such depths (also sink so low, sink/stoop to a new/an all-time low) - опуститься/пасть так низко, пробить дно (to do something so bad, to behave in a worse way than ever before):
     "Stealing from your friends? How could you sink so low?"
     "With this article the newspaper has sunk to a new low."
     "I can't believe that anyone would sink to such depths."
     "I can't believe you would sink so low as to snitch on your best friends."
     "Reality TV has sunk to new lows."
     "The government has stooped to an all-time low with this policy."
   sinking fast - быстро угасать ((of a person's health) getting much worse quickly so that death is likely):
     "Mrs Jones is sinking fast, and the doctor doesn't think she'll live much longer."
   sinking ship - тонущий корабль (a company or other organization that is failing):
     "He'd seen the accounts, realized he was on a sinking ship, and decided to get off."
     (like rats) deserting/leaving a sinking ship ​(humorous, disapproving):
   a/that sinking feeling (informal) - дурное предчуствие (an unpleasant feeling that you get when you realize that something bad has happened or is going to happen):
     "I had a horrible sinking feeling when I saw the ambulance outside the house."
     "I had a sinking feeling when I picked up the bill."
   be sunk in sth - погруженный в мысли (to be in a state of unhappiness or deep thought):
     "She just sat there, sunk in thought."
     "Rodin's sculpture "The Thinker" is of a man sitting with his head in his hand, sunk in thought."
   sb’s heart sinks - сердце упало/замерло (used to say that somebody suddenly feels sad or depressed about something):
     "My heart sank when I saw how much work there was left."
     "She watched him go with a sinking heart."
   sink in/sink into sth - впитаться ((of liquids) to go down into another substance through the surface):
     "The rain sank into the dry ground."
     "You'd better wipe up that coffee you spilled on the carpet before it sinks in."
   sink in - дойти, осознать (​(of words, an event, etc.) to be fully understood or realized):
     "He paused to allow his words to sink in."
     "The full scale of the disaster has yet to sink in."
     "It took a moment for the implications of what she was saying to sink in."

   be in sb's shoes | put yourself in sb shoes/position/place - быть/поставить/представить себя на месте другого (to imagine that you are someone in a difficult situation, and imagine how that person feels):
     "Put yourself in my place – I was scared, and I had nobody to talk to."
     "I wouldn't like to be in your shoes when they find out about it."
     "Well what would you do? Just put yourself in my shoes."

C2 speak your mind - открыто высказывать своё мнение (to say exactly what you think, in a very direct way):
     "She’s never hesitated about speaking her mind."
     "Everyone should have the right to speak their mind."

C2 be out of the question (also be no question of (doing) sth) - не может быть и речи (​impossible or not allowed and therefore not worth discussing):
     "A trip to New Zealand is out of the question this year."
     "There's no question of agreeing to the demands."

   bucket list (informal) - дела земные (a list of things that you want to do before you die):
     "I have so many things on my bucket list yet to do."
     "Travelling to India has been on my bucket list for years."

   be/weigh on your conscience - быть на совести, тяготеть (​making you feel guilty for doing or failing to do something):
     "Yesterday I ignored an old woman who asked me for money in the street, and it's been on my conscience ever since."
     "I'll write and apologize. I've had it on my conscience for weeks."
     "It’s still on my conscience that I didn’t warn him in time."

   the home stretch (also the home straight especially in British English) - финишная прямая (​​the last part of a race; the last part of an activity, etc. when it is nearly completed):
     "We're going into the home stretch of the presidential election."
     "It's taken three months, but we're on the home stretch now."

C2 bottom line - суть, основная мысль (the most important thing that you have to consider or accept; the essential point in a discussion, situation, etc.):
     "The bottom line is that we have to make a decision today."
     "The bottom line is that we need another ten thousand dollars to complete the project."

C2 slip sb's memory/mind - вылетело из головы ():
     "I forgot I'd arranged to meet Richard last night - it completely slipped my mind."
     "I’m sorry I didn’t tell you. It completely slipped my mind."

   slip through sb's fingers - ускользнуть из рук (​to miss or fail to use an opportunity):
     "You shouldn't let a job/man like that slip through your fingers!"
     "Don't let the chance to work abroad slip through your fingers."

   slip through the net (also fall/slip through the cracks) - быть упущенным из виду, ускользнуть (when sb/sth slips through the net, an organization or a system fails to find them and deal with them):
     "We tried to contact all former students, but one or two slipped through the net."
     "Once again terrorists have slipped through the police net."

C2 slip out - вылетело, вырвалось (If a remark slips out, you say it without intending to):
     "I'm sorry I said that. It just slipped out."

C2 slip up (informal) - оступиться, лажануть (​to make a careless mistake):
     "We can't afford to slip up."
     "The government slipped up badly over the scandal."
     "These figures don't make sense - have we slipped up somewhere?"

C2 slip away - выскользнуть, быть упущенным (If sb's power or the possibility of sb winning or achieving sth slips away, it disappears):
     "Political power was really in their hands and they let it slip away."

C2 slip away - выскользнуть (to leave secretly):
     "He slipped away while we were all sleeping."

C2 slip away - ускользать, утекать (If a period of time slips away, it passes quickly):
     "Time was slipping away and she had to make a decision soon."

   slip away - иссякнуть (to stop existing; to disappear or die): "Their support gradually slipped away."

   give sb the slip (informal) - ускользнуть от кого-л.:
     "I managed to give him the slip by hiding behind a wall."

   a slip of the pen/tongue - оговорка/описка (a small mistake in sth that you write or say):
     "Did I call you Richard? Sorry, Robert, just a slip of the tongue."
     "I didn't mean to say that—it was just a slip of the tongue."
     "I called her new boyfriend by her previous boyfriend's name - it was just a slip of the tongue."

   let slip <-> sth - проговориться, проболтаться, выболтать, разболтать (​to give sb information that is supposed to be secret), spill the beans (informal):
     "He let it slip that he hadn't actually read the report."
     "I happened to let it slip that he had given me £1 000 for the car."
     "She tried not to let slip what she knew."
     "So who spilled the beans about her affair with David?"

   (slip/be thrown) out of gear - выйти из под контроля (​(of emotions or situations) (to become) out of control):
     "She said nothing in case her temper slipped out of gear."

   roll/slip/trip off the tongue - (to be easy to say or pronounce):
     "The new company will need to have a name that trips off the tongue and is easy to remember."

   beg the question - ставить/поднимать вопрос, "но возникает вопрос, ..." (If a statement or situation begs the question, it causes you to ask a particular question):
     "All of which begs the question as to who will fund the project."
     "To discuss the company's future begs the question of whether it has a future."
     "Spending the summer travelling around India is a great idea, but it does beg the question of how we can afford it."

   as to sth | as regards sth - касаемо, что касается, в отношении (​used when you are referring to sth):
     "As to tax, that will be deducted from your salary."
     "As to where we'll get the money from, we'll talk about that later."
   as to = about (formal):
     "He was uncertain as to which road to take."
     "There's no decision as to when the work might start."
     "I have a few ideas as to how we might do this."
     "There is a serious issue as to whether or not we give tutors enough guidance."

C2 over the top (also OTT) - перебор, чересчур (done with too much acting, emotion or effort):
     "Her make-up was a bit OTT."
     "The speech was a bit OTT."
     "I thought the decorations were way (= very) over the top."
     "He realized he'd gone over the top with the seating arrangements."

   wear your heart on your sleeve (to allow your feelings to be seen by other people)Ж
     "He’s not one to wear his heart on his sleeve."

   bottle up sth - to refuse to talk about something that angers or worries you:
     "Feelings that had been bottled up for years came flooding out."

   the apple of sb's eye (old-fashioned) - зеница ока, "услада очей моих" (a person or thing that is loved more than any other), see also: pride and joy:
     "His youngest daughter was the apple of his eye."

   be better off - ​to have more money:
     "Families will be better off under the new law."
     "Her promotion means she's $100 a week better off."
     "Obviously we're better off now that we're both working."
     "When his parents died, he found himself $100,000 better off (= he had $100,000 more than before)."
   be better off (doing sth) - to be in a better situation, if or after something happens:
     "She's better off without him."
     "The weather was so bad we'd have been better off staying at home."
     "He'd be better off working for a bigger company."

   better/harder/worse etc still (also still better/harder/worse etc) - (что) ещё лучше/тяжелее/хуже (even better, harder etc than something else):
     "Dan found biology difficult, and physics harder still."
     "But perhaps the early evening was better still?"
     "I thought that it would soon pass, and it did - for you to work harder still."
     "I started to hunt for a cheap restaurant or, better still, a snack shop."
     "He didn't talk because he was afraid of losing the pole or, worse still, falling in."
     "Or better still, make a real talent show instead."
     "Or better still, there was the village school practically next door!"
     "With hindsight, it would have better still to lock in a few more gains."
    better yet - (а) ещё лучше (used to say that while one thing is good, another thing is even better):
      "You can see and, better yet, hear the effects of these changes on their website."
      "I wanted to make my parents proud by becoming a lawyer or, better yet, a doctor."

C2 dawn on sb - озарило, осенило (if sth dawns on you, you begin to realize it for the first time):
     "Suddenly it dawned on me that they couldn't possibly have met before."
     "I was about to pay for the shopping when it suddenly dawned on me that I'd left my wallet at home."
     "Worse still, it dawned on me that Economics was the wrong course for me - I didn’t want to work in the corporate world."

B2 deep down - в глубине души (felt strongly and often hidden from other people):
     "Deep down, I know you love me really."
     "Deep down I still loved him."
     "e was always a good bloke deep down."

C2 the ins and outs - тонкости (the detailed or complicated facts of something):
     "the ins and outs of the problem"
     "He quickly learned the ins and outs of the job."
     "I know how to use computers, but I don't really understand the ins and outs of how they work."
   the nuts and bolts (of sth) - ​(informal) тонкости (the basic practical details of a subject or an activity):
     "The documentary focuses on the real nuts and bolts of the film-making process."
     "When it came to the nuts and bolts of running a business, he was clearly unable to cope."

C2 first and foremost - в первую очередь (more than anything else):
     "He does a little teaching, but first and foremost he's a writer."
     "In spite of being elected to office, she remains first and foremost a writer."

C2 (put sth) in a nutshell - короче (говоря), одним словом, вкратце ((to say or express sth) in a very clear way, using few words):
     "To put it in a nutshell, we're bankrupt."
     "Well, to put it in a nutshell, we're lost."
   in a word (informal) - короче (говоря), одним словом (used for giving a very short, usually negative, answer or comment):
     "In a word, she's lying."
     "‘Would you like to help us?’ ‘In a word, no.’"

   regain your feet - подняться на ноги (to stand up again after falling or being knocked down)
     "I've been bedridden for so long that it took a bit of effort to finally regain my feet."
     "The boxer struggled to regain her feet after being knocked to the mat."
     "I'd be able to regain my feet if I could just pay off this damned credit card debt."
   regain (lost) ground - восстановить (потерянные) позиции (to begin to be strong or successful again after a period of difficulty):
     "On the Nasdaq, technology stocks struggled to regain ground after Wednesday's sell-off."

   (up) to the hilt - по уши, дальше некуда, "по самое не балуйся" (as much as possible):
     "We're mortgaged up to the hilt."
     "They have promised to back us to the hilt."

   the/a prodigal (son) - блудный сын (a person who leaves home and wastes their money and time on a life of pleasure, but who later is sorry about this and returns home):
     "The prodigal son has returned to the team after a three-year absence."

   take your cue from sb/sth - руководствоваться, следовать примеру (to take notice of someone's words or behaviour so that you know what you should do):
     "Investors are taking their cue from the big banks and selling dollars."
     "She watched his lips carefully and took her cue from him."
     "They all took their cue from their leader."

   (right) on cue - по команде (​at exactly the moment you expect or that is appropriate):
     "‘Where is that boy?’ As if on cue, Simon appeared in the doorway."
     "I was just wondering where Sarah was, when, right on cue, she came in."
     "I can't just cry on cue!"

   live off sb/sth - жить/выживать за счёт ((often disapproving) to receive the money you need to live from sb/sth because you do not have any yourself):
     "to live off welfare" - жить за счёт состояния
     "All his life he had lived off his father."
     "They had learned to live off the land (= grow or find their own food)."
     "She's still living off her parents."
   live off sth - питаться преимущественно чем-то одним (​to have one particular type of food as the main thing you eat in order to live):
     "He seems to live off junk food."

   in/out of commission - в исправном/неисправном состоянии (​available/not available to be used):
     "Several of the airline's planes are temporarily out of commission and undergoing safety checks."

   weed sth/sb out - отсеивать (to remove or get rid of people or things from a group because they are not wanted or are less good than the rest):
     "Most applicants get weeded out before the interview stage."
     "The first round of interviews only really serves to weed out the very weakest of applicants."

   along the way - попутно, по ходу дела, за это время (​as you make progress with something):
     "You'll learn something along the way."
     "I've been in this job for 30 years, and I've picked up a good deal of expertise along the way."

C2 come as/be a revelation (to sb) - стать/быть откровением (to be an extremely pleasant surprise; to be different from what was expected):
     "His performance in the race today was a revelation to everyone."
     "My trip to Texas was a revelation."
     "This book came as a complete revelation to me"

C1 let alone - не говоря уже о (used after a negative statement to emphasize how unlikely a situation is because something much more likely has never happened):
     "Some people never even read a newspaper, let alone a book."
     "There isn't enough room for us, let alone any guests."
     "I didn’t have any clothes, let alone a passport."

   out of step - не в ногу, не на одной волне:
     "I'm no good at dancing - I always get completely out of step."
     "The governor's remarks show that she is seriously out of step with the voters."

   the time is ripe - время пришло (If you say that the time is ripe, you mean that it is a suitable point for a particular activity):
     "I'm waiting till the time is ripe before I tell my parents that I failed my two exams."

   pull together - объединять/консолидировать усилия (to act, work, etc. together with other people in an organized way and without fighting):
     "We don't have much time but if we all pull together we should get the job done."
     "When a team pulls together, that means they channel their energy and skills towards one specific goal."

B2 take turns (UK also take it in turn(s)) (to do sth/(in) doing sth) - по очереди (if people take turns or take it in turns to do something, they do it one after the other to make sure it is done fairly):
     "We take turns answering the phone."
     "The male and female birds take turns in sitting on the eggs."
     "We take it in turns to do the housework."
     "The kids took turns on the swing."

C1 in turn (also by turns) - по очереди (one after the other in a particular order):
     "Each of us takes a break in turn."
     "The children called out their names in turn."
     "She spoke to each of the guests in turn."
   in turn - в свою очередь (as a result of something in a series of events):
     "Increased production will, in turn, lead to increased profits."
     "Stress causes your body to release chemicals, which in turn boost blood pressure."

   out of turn - вне/без череди (if you do sth out of turn, you do it when you are not supposed to be the next person to do sth):
     "Batista had batted out of turn."
     "I'm writing to you out of turn because I have some very important news."

   draw up - подъехать (if a vehicle draws up, it arrives and stops):
     "The cab drew up outside the house."
     "She waved to me as I drew up."

   draw sth <-> up - придвинуть стул (to move a chair near to sb or sth):
     "Draw up a chair, and I'll tell you all about it."

C1 draw sth <-> up - составить, подготовить (to make or write sth that needs careful thought or planning, esp. plans or a formal document):
     "to draw up a contract/list"
     "Make sure the contract is properly drawn up."
     "The lawyers drew up a contract over the weekend."
     "I've drawn up a list of candidates that I'd like to interview."

   draw yourself up - подтянуться, выпрямиться в полный рост, расправить плечи (to make yourself look bigger by standing straight with your shoulders back, usually to try to seem more important):
     "Like a lot of short men, he tends to draw himself up to his full height in public."

C1 draw the line - провести черту, не переходить черту/грань, не позволять (себе?) (to never do sth because you think it is wrong):
     "I swear a lot, but even I draw the line at saying certain words."

   take (great) pains (to do sth) | go to great pains (to do sth) - приложить (большие) усилия (to put a lot of effort into doing sth)
     "He took great pains to dress well for the occasion."
     "The couple went to great pains to keep their plans secret."
   take (great) pains with/over sth - приложить (большие) усилия (to do something very carefully):
     "He always takes great pains with his lectures."

   great minds think alike ​(informal, humorous) - у дураков мысли сходятся (said to someone just after you have discovered that they have had the same idea as you)

   great and small - от мала до велика (of all sizes or types):
     "all creatures great and small"

   the elephant in the room - an obvious problem that no one wants to discuss:
     "I don't want to ask the question, but it is the big elephant in the room."
     "The elephant in the room was the money that had to be paid in bribes."

C2 so to speak - так сказать (used to emphasize that you are expressing something in an unusual or humorous way)
     "They were all very similar. All cut from the same cloth, so to speak."
     "In that relationship it's very much Lorna who wears the trousers, so to speak (= Lorna makes all the important decisions)."

   push the envelope (informal) - раздвинуть границы, выйти за рамки (to go beyond the limits of what is allowed or thought to be possible):
     "He is a performer who consistently pushes the envelope of TV comedy."
     "We will keep trying to push the envelope - our market demands it."
     "Just like every other kid, I pushed the envelope. If I got away with being ten minutes late one night, I might be twenty minutes late the next night."

C2 gain/get/have/etc. the upper hand - (to get an advantage over somebody so that you are in control of a particular situation):
     "After hours of fierce negotiations, the president gained/got/had the upper hand."
     "The lack of living space is also becoming a big problem, with hundreds of people applying to live in the same apartment, the homeowners have the upper hand."

     a storm in a teacup (US a tempest in a teapot) - буря в стакане (a lot of unnecessary anger and worry about a matter that is not important)

C2 be on cloud nine, walk on air - быть на 7м небе (to feel extremely excited or happy)
       "Was Helen pleased about getting that job?" "Pleased? She was on cloud nine!"
       "After the delivery of her baby, she was walking on air."
       "Most couples feel they are walking on air on their wedding day."








   proverbs (https://www.learnamericanenglishonline.com/Proverbs/Proverbs_A.html)

   A chain is only as strong as its weakest link.

   If something can go wrong, it will go wrong.

   If life gives you lemons, make lemonade.

   If it ain't broke, don't fix it: работает - не трожь

   Ignorance is bliss: меньше знаешь - крепче спишь

   too good to be true: so good that it is hard to believe, or seeming very good but not real.
     saying: "If it/sth is/seems/sounds too good to be true, it probably is"
     "Her new job sounds too good to be true."
     "I'm not surprised the offer wasn't genuine, it sounded too good to be true."
     "‘I'm afraid you were quoted the wrong price.’ ‘I thought it was too good to be true.’"

   no pain, no gain - под лежачий камень вода не течёт (used to say that you need to suffer if you want to achieve something)

   immediate family - ближайшие родственники (родители, дети, муж, жена)
   extended family - immediate family + бабушки, дедушки, дяди, тёти и т.д.
   nuclear family - двое родителей + дети
